vestige.meaning: Trace or sign of something that once existed

vex.meaning: annoy or bother; puzzle or distress

via.meaning: Through, by means of, by way of (by a route that goes through or touches)

viable.meaning: Capable of living (or growing, developing, etc.); practical, workable

vicissitude.meaning: Changes or variations over time, esp. regular changes from one thing to another

vintage.meaning: Related to items of high quality from a previous era, old-fashioned, antique (adj); the wine of a particular year (noun)

virtual.meaning: Existing only in the mind or by means of a computer network; existing in results or in essence but not officially or in name

virulent.meaning: Extremely infectious, poisonous, etc.; hateful, bitterly hostile

viscid or.meaning: viscous Thick, adhesive, or covered in something sticky

vitriol.meaning: Something highly caustic, such as criticism (literally, one of a number of chemicals including sulfuric acid)

vituperate.meaning: Verbally abuse, rebuke or criticize harshly

vociferous.meaning: Noisily crying out, as in protest

volatile.meaning: Varying, inconstant, fleeting; tending to violence, explosive

voluble.meaning: Easily fluent in regards to speech

wan.meaning: Unnaturally pale, or showing some other indication of sickness, unhappiness, etc.; weak, lacking forcefulness

wanton.meaning: Reckless, vicious, without regard for what is right; unjustifiable, deliberately done for no reason at all; sexually unrestrained or excessively luxurious

warranted.meaning: Justified, authorized (warrant can mean to justify or a justification, but can also mean to vouch for or guarantee)

wary.meaning: Watchful, motivated by caution, on guard against danger

welter.meaning: Confused mass or pile, jumble; confusion or turmoil (noun); roll around, wallow, toss about, writhe (verb)

whereas.meaning: While on the contrary, considering that

whet.meaning: Stimulate, make keen or eager (esp. of an appetite)

whimsical.meaning: Marked or motivated by whims (odd, fanciful ideas); erratic, unpredictable

whitewash.meaning: A substance used to whiten walls, wood, etc. (noun); deception, covering up of wrongs, errors, misdeeds, etc. (verb)

wily.meaning: Crafty, cunning, characterized by tricks or artifice

winnow.meaning: Sift, analyze critically, separate the useful part from the worthless part

winsome.meaning: Charming, engaging, esp. in a sweet and innocent way

xenophobia.meaning: Fear or hatred of foreigners or that which is foreign

yoke.meaning: A burden or something that oppresses; a frame for attaching animals (such as oxen) to each other and to a plow or other equipment to be pulled, or a bar across a person's shoulders to help carry buckets of water, etc. (noun); to unite together or to burden (verb)

zeal.meaning: Great fervor or enthusiasm for a cause, person, etc.; tireless diligence in furthering that cause; passion, ardor
